@article{Mercer1997,
abstract = {Roughly 10 percent of divorcing parents cannot agree on a custody arrangement. Disputes over child custody are among the hardest cases judges face. Most jurisdictions use the "best interests of the child" to determine custody in disputed divorces. West Virginia uses the "primary caretaker" standard. This standard is a rule-based, determinate presumption that the parent who has provided day-to-day care for the child will get custody, if fit. Day-to-day care is defined by ten nurturing tasks that focus, in essence, on which parent prepares meals; changes the diapers and dresses and bathes the child; arranges for the child's social activities, medical care, and substitute childcare; puts the child to bed and wakes the child; and disciplines and educates the child. Arguably, the primary caretaker standard gives judges a manageable task: sum the ten factors to determine which parent took care of the child more. The standard should prevent children from being used as pawns in a divorce battle because it leads to predictable results. But is the primary caretaker standard accomplishing either of these goals? Forty-nine reported cases from West Virginia are analyzed using three approaches. The cases are: (1) examined for the presence or absence of the ten caretaking factors; (2) content analyzed for other factors or pre-disposing conditions which influence how the court approaches the decision; and (3) map analyzed to focus on the relationships between the concepts, and to determine if courts are using the primary caretaker standard consistently and predictably. The study demonstrates that the ten primary caretaker factors are not being used regularly to determine custody. Rather, courts discuss few, if any, of the factors in the custody decision. Three significant trends show how West Virginia courts reach a custody decision: (1) a mother's sexual conduct predicts an adverse custody decision, particularly at the trial court level, even where her behavior only tangentially touches the child; (2) courts are reverting to a "best interests" standard to determine custody in increasing cases, particularly where parents share the caretaking role; and (3) the temporary physical custodian receives a custody presumption even if that custodian is not the primary caretaker.},
